Problem:¶

The principal objective of this research is to create a predictive model that can precisely calculate an individual's risk of developing diabetes based only on their body mass index (BMI). The purpose of this approach is to provide healthcare practitioners with a useful screening tool so they may identify high-risk individuals and prioritise interventions.

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.heatmap(correlation_matrix, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt=".2f")
plt.title('Correlation Matrix of Diabetes Dataset Features')
plt.show()

The correlation matrix of the features in the dataset, such as age, sex, blood pressure (bp), BMI, six blood serum measurements (s1 through s6), and the diabetes development measure, is shown in the heatmap. The salient observations are:

  • The scatter plot's pattern is supported by the moderately positive association (about 0.59) between BMI and the course of diabetes.
  • Significant correlations have also been found between several of the serum measurements (such as s1 and s2), suggesting that the dataset may be multicollinear.
  • In addition to BMI, blood pressure (bp) and other serum parameters also exhibit some degree of connection with the onset of diabetes, indicating that they could be valuable predictors.
  • In this dataset, age has a relatively weak association with the advancement of diabetes, indicating that it may not be as reliable a predictor as some of the other characteristics.

# Check for outliers in BMI using the IQR method
Q1 = diabetes_x['bmi'].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = diabetes_x['bmi'].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1
lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

# Identifying outliers
outliers = diabetes_x[(diabetes_x['bmi'] < lower_bound) | (diabetes_x['bmi'] > upper_bound)]

In [63]:
# Defining a method for calculating MAPE 
def MAPE(y_true, y_pred): 
    return np.mean(np.abs((y_true - y_pred) / y_true)) * 100

Applying the polynomial regression on the BMI feature

In [64]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures
from sklearn.pipeline import make_pipeline
polynomial_models = {}

for degree in range(6):
    model = make_pipeline(PolynomialFeatures(degree), LinearRegression())
    model.fit(X_train[['bmi']], y_train)
    polynomial_models[f"degree_{degree}"] = model

Calculating the metrics for each degree

In [65]:
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score, mean_absolute_error, mean_absolute_percentage_error

# Initialize dictionaries to store the metrics for training and validation
train_metrics = {'R_squared': [], 'MAE': [], 'MAPE': []}
val_metrics = {'R_squared': [], 'MAE': [], 'MAPE': []}

for degree in range(6):
    # Retrieve the model for the current degree
    model = polynomial_models[f"degree_{degree}"]
    
    # Predict on the training data and calculate metrics
    y_train_pred = model.predict(X_train[['bmi']])
    train_r2 = r2_score(y_train, y_train_pred)
    train_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_train, y_train_pred)
    train_mape = mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_train, y_train_pred)
    
    # Store the metrics
    train_metrics['R_squared'].append(train_r2)
    train_metrics['MAE'].append(train_mae)
    train_metrics['MAPE'].append(train_mape)
    
    # Predict on the validation data and calculate metrics
    y_val_pred = model.predict(X_val[['bmi']])
    val_r2 = r2_score(y_val, y_val_pred)
    val_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_val, y_val_pred)
    val_mape = mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_val, y_val_pred)
    
    # Store the metrics
    val_metrics['R_squared'].append(val_r2)
    val_metrics['MAE'].append(val_mae)
    val_metrics['MAPE'].append(val_mape)

  • The worst performing model is the Degree 0 model, which is just a horizontal line with an R-squared of 0 on the training data and -0.01 on the validation data. This shows that there is no correlation between the expected and actual results, which is to be expected from a model that remains constant when BMI varies.

  • All measures show a significant improvement when we approach to Degree 1, which is a simple linear model. The R-squared values increase to 0.37 for training and 0.30 for validation, indicating that the model for the training and validation sets accounts for roughly 37% and 30% of the variability in the illness development, respectively. Improved predictive accuracy is indicated by the significant decreases in the MAE and MAPE.

  • The R-squared value for the training data does not change much from Degree 2 to Degree 5; it stays at roughly 0.37. The R-squared varies significantly but doesn't consistently improve for the validation data. Compared to the simpler models, Degree 4 actually exhibits a lower R-squared value, which could indicate overfitting to the training set.

  • The models' MAE and MAPE metrics exhibit negligible variations as well; Degree 5's MAE and MAPE on the validation set are marginally lower than those of the other models. Nevertheless, the enhancements are slight and might not warrant the heightened intricacy of the model.

  • In light of these findings, the Degree 1 model is clearly the best option. Its consistent metrics across the training and validation datasets demonstrate that it exhibits significant predictive power without overfitting, offering a fair balance between complexity and performance.
